sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade

Installing Java and Maven
==================
sudo apt install openjdk-8-jdk openjdk-8-jre
sudo apt install maven

sudo apt install nano
sudo nano /etc/profile.d/maven.sh (add below lines to the file > Save > Run source command)
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-8-openjdk-amd64/jre
export MAVEN_HOME=/usr/share/maven
export M2_HOME=/usr/share/maven
export PATH=${M2_HOME}/bin:${PATH}
source /etc/profile.d/maven.sh


Installing Jenkins
==================
wget -q -O - https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian/jenkins.io.key | sudo apt-key add -
#(try this if does not work) wget --no-check-certificate -qO - http://pkg.jenkins-ci.org/debian/jenkins-ci.org.key | sudo apt-key add -
sudo sh -c 'echo deb http://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ > /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list'
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y jenkins   or    sudo apt-get install jenkins

Notes
===========
- Chekcing the status (sudo /etc/init.d/jenkins)
- Log file will be placed in /var/log/jenkins/jenkins.log
- /etc/default/jenkins will capture configuration parameters for the launch like e.g JENKINS_HOME
- If your /etc/init.d/jenkins file fails to start jenkins, edit the /etc/default/jenkins to replace the line
    HTTP_PORT=8080 by
    HTTP_PORT=8081

Upgrade
=========
Once installed like this, you can update to the later version of Jenkins (when it comes out) by running the following commands:
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install jenkins
